tering out metadata, but ingredient lines with dashes and Polish words are slipping through as valid results. So \"- 2 jajka\" actually passes the hard filters—that's the real problem. Ingredient lines that start with a dash and contain no measurement keywords are slipping through as valid candidates when they shouldn't be. I'm realizing the core issue: these lines are winning because of how the recipe structure works, where sections like \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" create conditions that let ingredient markers pass validation. I'm checking whether the subheaders are actually followed by ingredient lines—\"- 2 jajka\" doesn't match the ingredient pattern since it lacks measurement keywords and doesn't start with a digit, so the isSubHeader check fails for \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\". This means both \"SKŁADNIKI\" and \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" get selected as headers, and deduplication should handle keeping just one.\n\nBut wait, if the output is actually \"- 2 jajka\", then my logic about what passes the hard filters must be off—let me trace through what \"SKŁADNIKI\" would need to pass through. The vowel ratio checks out, and since it's a single word longer than three letters, the short word filter doesn't trigger. It starts with an uppercase letter and has no period, so it passes the garbled checks. \"Składniki\" isn't in the non-title words list either, so it clears the hard filters and could be a valid candidate for embedding.\n\nNow I'm thinking about how the similarity scoring works—\"składniki\" means \"ingredients\" in Polish, so it should have a very high similarity to header references but low similarity to title references. That would give it a negative raw score that probably falls below the threshold. Let me trace through the structural heading logic to see if \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" would be the only heading that survives the checks.\n\nThe structural heading function requires all caps and at least 2 words, so \"SKŁADNIKI\" as a single word wouldn't qualify, leaving \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" as the only structural heading eligible for the bonus. But I'm still puzzled about how the algorithm returns \"- 2 jajka\" when I need to look more carefully at what's actually in the selected items after threshold filtering and whether \"SKŁADNIKI\" even makes it through. I'm checking whether \"- 2 jajka\" passes the garbled text filter by examining its vowel ratio and word structure more carefully.\n\nNow I'm moving on to \"- 050 g mąki\" and realizing that \"g\" isn't actually in the measurement patterns list, so I need to reconsider whether this looks like a valid ingredient line. So \"g\" isn't in the common short words list, which means it gets flagged as garbled text. The same issue happens with \"- 50 g masła\" — that single letter triggers the garbled filter too. Now I'm checking \"PRZYGOTOWANIE:\" to see if the colon and all-caps formatting cause similar problems. I'm checking the remaining candidates against the hard filters. \"PRZYGOTOWANIE:\" passes because it's a single word starting with uppercase, no period issues. The numbered steps like \"1. Dekoruj świeżą bazylią\" fail immediately since they start with numbers, and the garbled text fails the vowel-to-consonant ratio check. That leaves \"SKŁADNIKI\" and \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" as the likely section headers.\n\nNow I'm puzzled about why \"- 2 jajka\" is appearing as output when it should fail the measurement keyword filter—it contains a number and ingredient indicator. Let me reconsider how the multi-header detection and allCapsSelected threshold are actually working here. SKŁADNIKI is actually in the HEADER_REFERENCE list, so it should score very negatively and likely won't make it into the selected items. That means allCapsSelected would only contain \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" with length 1, which triggers a different branch of the filtering logic.\n\nWhen there's only one all-caps candidate, the code picks whichever item has the highest score overall—but that would require \"- 2 jajka\" to outscore \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\", which seems unlikely. Let me trace through the threshold and isSubHeader checks more carefully to see what's actually passing through. I'm checking whether \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" should win based on its structural heading status and all-caps bonus, but the output shows \"- 2 jajka\" is selected instead—so I need to look at the `isLikelyGarbled` check to understand why the ingredient line is winning despite being lower-scored. I'm reconsidering why \"- 2 jajka\" is winning over the other candidates. Let me trace through the logic differently—maybe there's something about how `findBurstEnd` calculates the burst range that I'm missing. Looking at the file structure, I'm seeing the non-empty lines after trimming and trying to understand which one actually gets selected as the burst. I'm checking whether \"SKŁADNIKI\" is garbled by analyzing its letter composition—removing non-ASCII characters like Ł and Ą leaves me with a vowel ratio that falls within the normal range, so it's not flagged as corrupted. This means `findBurstEnd` would return 0 and include all the lines in the output.\n\nNow looking at Oscypek, which does start with clearly garbled text like \"Page 47 l'|l111'\" and repeated characters—those lines are short enough and garbled enough to be skipped by the burst detection logic. I'm checking the garbled word detection—\"l'|l111'\" strips down to just \"ll\", which isn't in the common short words list, so that triggers the garbled flag. Then I'm testing a few other cases: \"rnrnrnrnrnrnrnrnrn\" has zero vowels, falling well below the threshold, and a string of just punctuation becomes empty after filtering, both marking them as garbled.\n\nNow I'm tracing through how the burst detection works with the Oscypek example, looking at which lines get flagged and where the burst actually ends based on the garbled word logic. I'm checking whether \"OSCYPEK\" passes the hard filters—it's 7 characters long, not an ingredient, doesn't start with a number, isn't metadata, and isn't garbled. The key question is whether it's in the non-title words list, which would disqualify it.\n\nLooking at the Oscypek.txt file structure, after filtering out the burst of short lines, I'm left with \"OSCYPEK\" as a candidate title, followed by \"SKŁADNIKI:\" and ingredient lines like \"- 50 g masła\" and \"- 100 ml mleka\". The measurement patterns and short words like \"g\" and \"ml\" are triggering the garbled or ingredient filters on those lines, so they'd be excluded from the title candidates.\n\nNow examining \"- Sól do smaku\" more carefully—after removing punctuation it becomes \"Sldosmaku\". The word \"do\" is actually in my commonShort2 list, so it doesn't count as garbled text. \"Sól\" starts with uppercase S, and \"smaku\" is lowercase, which fits the expected pattern for a normal line rather than a title. I see the real problem now—ingredient lines that start with \"- \" but don't have measurement keywords are passing through all the hard filters, which is why \"Sól do smaku\" and \"Salt to taste\" keep showing up in the results. The issue is that Polish measurements like \"łyżka\" (tablespoon) and \"jajka\" (eggs) aren't in the MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS list, and neither are unmeasured items like \"to taste,\" so they're not being caught as ingredients and filtered out properly.\n\nLooking at this \"Garlic Bruschetta\" file, I'm checking why \"Salt to taste\" isn't being filtered—it fails the looksLikeIngredient check since there's no measurement keyword, doesn't start with a number, and when I analyze it for garbling, the vowel count seems off for a legitimate ingredient line. , o, o, a, e = 5 out of 11 = 0.45. OK. Words: [\"-\", \"Salt\", \"to\", \"taste\"]. \"to\" starts with 't' (lowercase), length 2 ≤ 2. Is \"to\" in commonShort2? YES! \"taste\" starts with 't' lowercase, length 5 > 2. So hasGarbledWord = false. Not garbled.\n\nSo \"- Salt to taste\" passes hard filters!\n\nNow why does it win over \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\"? \n\n\"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" is ALL_CAPS, 2 words, both words have ≥4 alpha letters → isStructuralHeading = true → gets +0.10 structural bonus, +0.08 allCaps bonus. It should also have a good rawScore against title reference. Plus it's at position 2 (early in document).\n\n\"- Salt to taste\" has no bonuses. Its embedding similarity to title reference should be low. It should lose to \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" unless... let me check if \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" actually passes the hard filters. The letters are all uppercase, vowel ratio is 5 out of 16 which is above the threshold, and it doesn't have the single-word short issue. It starts with uppercase G, so that checks out too.\n\nFor multi-word garbled check: both \"GARLIC\" and \"BRUSCHETTA\" start with uppercase letters, so neither matches the lowercase pattern. No garbled word found. So \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" passes all hard filters.\n\nWait, I'm seeing \"- Salt to taste\" as the output for Garlic Bruschetta, but that phrase appears multiple times in the input. After deduplication, it should only appear once, so there might be something else going on here.\n\nLet me think about the scoring differently. The rawScore calculation is titleSim minus the maximum of headerSim and noiseSim. For \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\", the titleSim should be...\n\nActually, I'm getting caught up in speculation about exact embedding scores when I can't see the actual values. What I can pinpoint from the code itself is the real issue: the `looksLikeIngredient` function only recognizes English measurement patterns, so lines like \"- Salt to taste\" or \"- 2 jajka\" slip through the hard filters because they don't match any of the standard measurement keywords. This means ingredient lines without conventional units—whether in English or Polish—aren't being caught as ingredients at all. I see the issue now—\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" gets flagged as a sub-header because it's immediately followed by ingredient lines with measurement keywords like \"tbsp\", so \"INGREDIENTS\" becomes the selected title instead. But most other files have \"INGREDIENTS:\" as an explicit header before the actual ingredient list, which means the title gets evaluated differently. I need to check how the ordering and detection logic handles these variations. I'm checking the hard filters for \"INGREDIENTS:\" — it's not garbled, it's all caps, but it's only one word. That means it won't qualify as a structural heading since those require at least two words. So even though it passes the basic filters and is in all caps, it wouldn't be selected as a header for Garlic Bruschetta. Let me trace through what actually gets selected in that section more carefully. I'm verifying that \"- 100g butter\" passes the garbled text check by examining its letter composition and word structure, confirming it's a valid ingredient line. I'm also noting that \"- Salt to taste\" appears twice in the list and \"- 100g butter\" is repeated, so I'm tracking which entries I've already evaluated.\n\nNow I'm checking \"- 3 egg0\" — the word \"egg0\" contains three letters when stripped of non-alphabetic characters, which means it passes the garbled filter. I'm also running through other lines like \"INSTRUCTIONS:\" which fails because it's all caps, numbered steps which fail the number check, and \"Prep time: 30 minutes\" where I'm testing whether the metadata pattern matches the time format. The word boundary after \"min\" fails because the next character 'u' is a word character, so \"30 minutes\" doesn't match the pattern. Now I'm checking whether \"Prep time\" matches the label pattern—\"PREP\" matches, then the space, and I need to see if the rest of the pattern accounts for \"time\".  After PREP, the optional AND and COOK parts are skipped, then `\\s*TIME` matches the space and \"time\" case-insensitively, so \"Prep time: 30 minutes\" correctly gets flagged as metadata. Looking at the Garlic Bruschetta candidates, I have the heading itself with a structural bonus and the ingredients label.\n\nNow I'm scoring these entries—the title gets high bonuses from being all caps and a structural heading, while something like \"Salt to taste\" has no bonuses and a weaker raw score. Yet the output is showing \"Salt to taste\" as the result, which suggests either the title didn't make it past the threshold filtering or there's an issue with how the scoring is being applied.\n\nLet me trace through the all-caps filtering logic more carefully. After threshold filtering, I'm checking which candidates are actually all uppercase—\"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\", \"INGREDIENTS:\", and \"INSTRUCTIONS:\" all pass, but \"Salt to taste\" fails because it contains lowercase letters.\n\nWith three all-caps items, the multi-title guard triggers, and I'm now checking if the items after the first one look like section headers. Both \"INGREDIENTS:\" and \"INSTRUCTIONS:\" have ingredient-like or numbered content in their following lines, so they're correctly identified as subheaders and filtered out of the selected results.\n\nThat leaves just \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" as the output, but the actual result is \"- Salt to taste\"—something's off with my position tracking. Let me recount the actual line numbers in the file to see where the mismatch is. I'm parsing through the recipe data and filtering out empty lines to get a clean list of non-empty entries. Now I'm checking the first line to see if it's garbled text by analyzing its character composition. The burst continues since \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" isn't garbled, so I'm now looking at how the merged lines would be structured starting from that line through the ingredients and instructions sections.\n\nNow I'm checking which lines qualify as structural headings—\"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" passes all the criteria with its all-caps format, two-word structure, and words with sufficient length, while \"INGREDIENTS:\" fails because it's only one word. So \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" gets the structural bonus, but something's off with my logic since the actual output is \"- Salt to taste\" instead.\n\nLet me reconsider the `isAllCaps` function—it strips non-alphabetic characters before checking, so \"INGREDIENTS:\" becomes \"INGREDIENTS\" and still qualifies as all-caps. That means my analysis should hold, yet the output doesn't match, so I'm clearly missing something in how the selection logic works.\n\nThe real issue might be the embedding similarity threshold. These are synthetic recipe texts, so the actual cosine similarities could be quite different from what I'd expect—\"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" might have a surprisingly low score relative to the title, causing it to fail the threshold check. And \"- Salt to taste\" appearing as a simple, repeated ingredient line could be getting selected through a different mechanism entirely. Let me step back and look at the actual patterns in the failing cases to understand what's really happening.\n\nI'm noticing two distinct groups: files where the recipe title appears right after \"SKŁADNIKI\"/\"INGREDIENTS\" headers, and files where it comes after garbled noise like \"Page 47...\" or \"rn...\". In both cases, the title is an ALL_CAPS line immediately followed by ingredient lines. For the isSubHeader logic to trigger, I need at least 2 ALL_CAPS headings in the selected content.\n\nThe real issue is that when both the section header and the recipe title are ALL_CAPS, the title gets marked as a sub-header, so the first ALL_CAPS line wins—but that's outputting ingredient lines like \"- Salt to taste\" instead of the actual header text. This suggests \"SKŁADNIKI\" or \"INGREDIENTS\" might be getting filtered out by deduplication, prefix logic, or threshold filtering.\n\nLooking at the Mozzarella Sticks example: \"INGREDIENTS\" fails the structural heading check because it's only one word, while \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" passes with two words and gets the structural bonus. After threshold filtering, both could remain in the selected set, but I need to trace through what `allCapsSelected` actually contains at that point. I see the issue now—when the header doesn't pass the threshold, only the title and ingredient lines remain, so allCapsSelected shrinks to just the recipe title. Then the selection logic picks whichever candidate has the highest score, and somehow \"- Salt to taste\" is winning out over \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" even though the title should have structural bonuses, the all-caps bonus, and a positive raw score that the ingredient line lacks.\n\nThe real problem is that `looksLikeIngredient` only recognizes English measurement units, so Polish measurements like \"łyżka,\" \"szklanka,\" and \"szczypta\" slip through as non-ingredients and get treated as potential titles instead.\n\nAdditionally, the code doesn't filter lines starting with dashes or bullets, and when `INGREDIENTS` appears before the actual title in all caps, the `isSubHeader` logic misidentifies the structure and picks the wrong heading as the result.\n\nNow I'm looking at the threshold scoring logic more carefully—it calculates a best threshold based on raw score plus the all-caps bonus, then filters candidates by that threshold multiplied by 0.7, which might explain why some unexpected lines like \"- Salt to taste\" are making it through as selected candidates. itionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus.\n\nIf \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" has rawScore of say 0.15, then thresholdScore = 0.15 + 0.08 = 0.23. threshold = max(0.08, 0.23 * 0.7) = max(0.08, 0.161) = 0.161. score = 0.15 * (1 + some positive) + 0.08 + 0.10 ≈ 0.39. Clearly above threshold.\n\nAnd if \"- Salt to taste\" has rawScore = -0.05 (negative, not title-like), its score = -0.05 * positionFactor + 0 + 0 ≈ -0.05. Below threshold = 0.161. So it wouldn't make it through.\n\nBut wait, there's a pre-dedup filter that removes all-caps headers only if they're followed by ingredients and don't contain other candidates as substrings. Filtering substring candidates...\n\nChecking if \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\" is followed by ingredients or numbers. The next line after it is empty, so it passes the filter and survives. \"- Salt to taste\" isn't all-caps, so it's not subject to this removal anyway.\n\nThen for the multi-title guard, \"INGREDIENTS:\" and \"INSTRUCTIONS:\" both look like section headers because they're followed by ingredient and numbered lists respectively. This means the earliest all-caps entry, \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\", should be selected as the winner. But in practice it's not winning, which suggests something else is filtering it out first.\n\nLet me step back and focus on what the actual outputs are telling me. I can see clear patterns: ingredient lines without measurement keywords are slipping through because the detection only checks for English units, and section headers like \"INGREDIENTS\" are being selected when they shouldn't be. Rather than continuing to trace through the logic mentally, I should build my feedback around these concrete failure modes I can observe across the test cases. I'm tracing through the join logic — the \"+\" separator comes from the code that combines selected items, so if the output shows \"- 100g butter - 100g butter + - Salt to taste\", that means two separate candidates are being selected and joined together, which suggests the parsing is capturing multi-line ingredient entries as individual candidates rather than treating them as single items. I see that when the actual title gets filtered out because it doesn't meet the threshold, the remaining items—which are just regular ingredients—all survive and get joined together, creating nonsensical combinations like \"- 100g butter - 100g butter + - Salt to taste\". The core problem is that the filtering logic treats ingredient lines the same way it treats structural titles, so when the real title disappears, everything else gets lumped together.\n\nNow I'm tracing through why the actual title gets lost in the first place—I think it's related to how the isSubHeader logic evaluates these lines. Looking at a file like Barszcz Czerwony, the title \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" is ALL_CAPS and should be structural, but it seems to be getting caught by the same filters that are meant to catch garbled or incomplete ingredient entries.\n\nThe issue is that when checking if \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" should be treated as a subheader, the logic looks at the following lines to see if they look like ingredients. But \"- 2 jajka\" doesn't match the measurement patterns, and the line starting with a dash doesn't count as starting with a number, so the followedByIngredients check fails. This causes the entire isSubHeader condition to evaluate to false, which means \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" gets lumped into the general all-caps selection alongside \"SKŁADNIKI\" instead of being recognized as a distinct section header. After deduplication and sorting, both survive, but the structure gets mangled in the process.\n\nActually, I think I've been miscalculating whether \"SKŁADNIKI\" passes the threshold. Since it's literally the Polish word for ingredients and appears in the HEADER_REFERENCE list, its similarity to that reference would be very high, while its similarity to the title reference would be low. That means the raw score calculation—titleSim minus the maximum of headerSim and noiseSim—would actually be negative.\n\nSo \"SKŁADNIKI\" probably doesn't pass the threshold at all. That leaves only \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" in the all-caps selected list. The code then picks the single highest-scoring candidate from the entire selected array, not just the all-caps ones. Even if \"- 2 jajka\" somehow has a higher score, \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" should dominate because it gets the raw score boost plus the all-caps bonus and structural bonus.\n\nWait, maybe \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" is actually failing the hard filters for some reason I haven't caught yet. Let me trace through the garbled text check—I need to count the actual letters in both words to see if there's something disqualifying there. consonant\n- Z → consonant\n→ \"BARSZCZ\" has 1 vowel (A) out of 7 letters\n\n- C → consonant\n- Z → consonant  \n- E → VOWEL ✓\n- R → consonant\n- W → consonant\n- O → VOWEL ✓\n- N → consonant\n- Y → VOWEL ✓ (Y is in [yYąęóĄĘÓ])\n→ \"CZERWONY\" has 3 vowels (E, O, Y) out of 8 letters\n\nTotal: 4 vowels out of 15 letters = 0.267 > 0.15. OK, passes.\n\nSo it's not a garbled issue. Let me try a completely different hypothesis.\n\nMaybe \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" does pass the hard filters but gets a poor embedding score because the model hasn't seen this specific Polish dish name in its training data. Even though the context includes \"nazwa dania\" to signal it's a dish name, the embedding might still struggle with unfamiliar terms. Without actually running the code, I can't pinpoint exact scores, but I can identify the real issues: the ingredient detection is too strict and misses Polish units and simple items like salt or eggs, lines starting with dashes incorrectly pass the number check, and the subheader logic sometimes demotes the actual title when it encounters ingredient section headers.\n\nLooking at the specific failures, ingredient lines like \"- 2 jajka\" or \"- Sól do smaku\" pass the hard filters because they don't match ingredient keywords, don't start with numbers, and have acceptable vowel ratios, so they slip through into the selected pool alongside the actual recipe title.\n\nFor cases like Mozzarella Sticks, the isSubHeader logic triggers when both INGREDIENTS and MOZZARELLA STICKS are all caps and the title is followed by a measurement keyword like \"tbsp\", causing it to pick INGREDIENTS as the header instead.\n\nThe core issue is that `looksLikeIngredient` is too restrictive—it's English-focused and misses patterns like \"to taste\" or \"do smaku\", plus it doesn't recognize the bullet marker \"- \" as a signal that something is part of an ingredient list.\n\nThere's also a measurement pattern gap: \"100g\" doesn't match the existing patterns since they look for \"gram\" or \"grams\" but not the abbreviated \"g\", so lines like \"100g butter\" slip through the filters.\n\nNow I'm writing up the feedback.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10317,"cache_read_input_tokens":28051,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10317},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d3c78e08-9dc3-489d-8b45-de39a42f3486","uuid":"f0e4c7c0-aaa0-4318-b967-6d0d4a95cba0"}
